        "summary": "## Goal\n- Determine whether any bot tokens in `/root/.openclaw/openclaw.json` are duplicated.\n- Restart OpenClaw gateway after adding new keys/tokens.\n- Configure OpenClaw to allow a Telegram group for agent bots, and figure out how to obtain the Telegram group ID.\n- Configure Telegram group behavior so only mentioned bots reply, with `master-orchestrator` as the coordinator for the 34-agent system.\n- Clarify architecture for 34 agents in one Telegram group, especially how specialist bots should interact and when they should speak.\n\n## Constraints & Preferences\n- User is working with OpenClaw local config files, especially `/root/.openclaw/openclaw.json`.\n- User wants practical, direct steps in Vietnamese.\n- Security-sensitive context appeared: a real Telegram bot token was pasted in chat and should be treated as compromised/rotated.\n- Must preserve exact file paths / exact error text when relevant.\n- User wants group behavior where only the explicitly mentioned bot replies.\n- User wants `master-orchestrator` to be the central coordinator among 34 agents.\n- User wants each replying bot to appear with its own Telegram identity/avatar/name/timestamp, which implies separate Telegram bot accounts per agent.\n\n## Progress\n### Done\n- [x] Checked `/root/.openclaw/openclaw.json` for duplicate token values.\n- [x] Found 35 token-related fields and 2 duplicate bot-token pairs:\n  - `$.channels.telegram.accounts.senior-architect_bot.botToken`\n    and `$.channels.telegram.accounts.senior-backend_bot.botToken`\n  - `$.channels.telegram.accounts.stitch-loop_bot.botToken`\n    and `$.channels.telegram.accounts.typescript-reviewer_bot.botToken`\n- [x] Attempted `openclaw gateway restart && openclaw gateway status`; command became long-running and later session polling showed no session.\n- [x] Investigated `\"This group is not allowed.\"` in installed OpenClaw source.\n- [x] Located exact runtime error string in `/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/bot-ClNJQIfx.js`.\n- [x] Confirmed Telegram group allowlist support exists via:\n  - global `channels.telegram.groups`\n  - per-account `channels.telegram.accounts.<accountId>.groups`\n- [x] Verified current config initially lacked Telegram group allowlist entries:\n  - `telegram.groupPolicy = None`\n  - `telegram.groups exists = False`\n  - `main_bot groupPolicy= None groups keys= []`\n- [x] Explained that the group error is caused by allowlist, not mention/privacy alone.\n- [x] User tried `curl \"https://api.telegram.org/bot.../getUpdates\"` and got `{\"ok\":true,\"result\":[]}`.\n- [x] Confirmed local gateway/runtime config source is `~/.openclaw/openclaw.json` via `openclaw gateway status`.\n- [x] Extracted the real Telegram group ID from gateway log `/tmp/openclaw/openclaw-2026-04-11.log`:\n  - `chatId: -1003833817951`\n  - `title: \"Maiychrus Company .Ltd\"`\n  - log reason: `\"not-allowed\"`\n- [x] Added the old group allowlist entry to `/root/.openclaw/openclaw.json`:\n  ```json\n  \"channels\": {\n    \"telegram\": {\n      \"groups\": {\n        \"-1003833817951\": {\n          \"enabled\": true,\n          \"requireMention\": false\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n  ```\n- [x] Diagnosed second-layer authorization error `\"You are not authorized to use this command.\"` as sender authorization, not group authorization.\n- [x] Located the relevant command gating logic in:\n  - `/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/bot-ClNJQIfx.js`\n  - `/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/access-B1I79MZ7.js`\n  - `/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/commands-models-70xwb3QF.js`\n- [x] Verified command auth behavior in `/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/bot-ClNJQIfx.js` uses:\n  - `cfg.commands?.allowFrom`\n  - Telegram sender/group allow evaluation\n  - `resolveCommandAuthorizedFromAuthorizers(...)`\n  - and returns `sendAuthMessage(\"You are not authorized to use this command.\")`\n- [x] Confirmed config initially had no sender allowlist:\n  - `commands = null`\n  - `telegram.allowFrom = null`\n  - sampled account `allowFrom = null`\n- [x] Added Telegram sender allowlist for the user in `/root/.openclaw/openclaw.json`:\n  - `channels.telegram.allowFrom = [\"6053576134\"]`\n- [x] Temporarily removed the old group allowlist entry `-1003833817951` when user wanted to create a new group.\n- [x] Added the new requested group ID `-5212380728` to `/root/.openclaw/openclaw.json`:\n  ```json\n  \"channels\": {\n    \"telegram\": {\n      \"groups\": {\n        \"-5212380728\": {\n          \"enabled\": true,\n          \"requireMention\": false\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n  ```\n- [x] Inspected current Telegram config and confirmed:\n  - `GLOBAL GROUPS` contained `-5212380728`\n  - `DEFAULT allowFrom` contained `[\"6053576134\"]`\n  - `main_bot.username` was still `null` in config sample\n- [x] Verified local OpenClaw implementation references for mention handling via grep, including:\n  - `resolveChannelGroupRequireMention`\n  - `hasBotMention`\n  - `registerTelegramNativeCommands`\n- [x] Updated `/root/.openclaw/openclaw.json` to enforce mention-only behavior for the new group:\n  ```json\n  \"channels\": {\n    \"telegram\": {\n      \"groupPolicy\": \"allowlist\",\n      \"allowFrom\": [\"6053576134\"],\n      \"groups\": {\n        \"-5212380728\": {\n          \"enabled\": true,\n          \"requireMention\": true\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n  ```\n- [x] Explained the recommended operating model for the 34-agent system:\n  - group as shared entry point\n  - `master-orchestrator` as sole coordinator\n  - specialist agents should not all auto-talk publicly\n  - default desired rule: only the explicitly mentioned bot should reply\n- [x] Clarified that true per-message Telegram identity display (bot icon/name/time) requires each agent to be a separate Telegram bot account; a single shared bot can only fake identity in text.\n\n### In Progress\n- [ ] Have the user run `openclaw gateway restart` so the latest Telegram config takes effect.\n- [ ] Validate in the new group `-5212380728` that:\n  - non-mentioned messages get no bot reply\n  - mentioned bot messages reply correctly\n- [ ] Map all 34 agent IDs to actual Telegram bot usernames/accounts.\n- [ ] Decide final operating mode:\n  - only `@master_orchestrator_bot` as public speaker by default, or\n  - any explicitly mentioned specialist bot may reply directly.\n\n### Blocked\n- Gateway restart was attempted from assistant side multiple times, but commands exited with `SIGTERM` / required user execution; latest config still needs user to run `openclaw gateway restart`.\n- Full 34-bot mention routing is not yet fully configured because usernames/account mappings for all bots are not yet assembled.\n- Exact Telegram usernames for the 34 bots are still unknown from config/logs so far; `main_bot.username` sample was `null`.\n\n## Key Decisions\n- **Telegram group allowlisting is required**: The exact error `\"This group is not allowed.\"` indicates the group is not in OpenClaw's Telegram allowlist.\n- **Use `channels.telegram.groups` for shared group access**: This is the recommended simpler config if many agent bots should work in the same group.\n- **Minimal allowlist entry is enough**: A group config like `{ \"enabled\": true }` is sufficient to clear the allowlist error; `requireMention: false` is optional if user wants looser triggering.\n- **`getUpdates` empty likely means OpenClaw consumed updates**: Since the bot already responded in-group, updates likely reached OpenClaw before the manual curl.\n- **Token should be rotated**: The user pasted a live bot token in chat, so it should be considered compromised.\n- **Use gateway runtime logs to discover real chat IDs**: `/tmp/openclaw/openclaw-2026-04-11.log` exposed the actual rejected group `chatId` and title when `getUpdates` was insufficient.\n- **There are two separate Telegram access layers**: group allowlist and sender authorization. Passing the group check does not bypass `\"You are not authorized to use this command.\"`\n- **Telegram sender authorization should be handled via `channels.telegram.allowFrom`**: Adding user `6053576134` resolved the sender-side command gate intent in config.\n- **Current target group changed**: Old group `-1003833817951` was intentionally removed; active target group is now `-5212380728`.\n- **Final desired group rule is mention-only**: For group `-5212380728`, `requireMention: true` was chosen so bots do not respond unless directly mentioned.\n- **Recommended 34-agent architecture is orchestrated, not free-form**: `master-orchestrator` should coordinate specialists internally rather than letting all 34 bots speak autonomously in one group.\n- **True per-bot visual identity requires separate Telegram bot accounts**: To show each reply with that bot’s own avatar/name/timestamp, each agent must have its own Telegram bot account; this cannot be achieved with one shared bot identity.\n\n## Next Steps\n1. User runs:\n   - `openclaw gateway restart`\n2. Test behavior in Telegram group `-5212380728`:\n   - send a normal message without mention → expected: no bot reply\n   - send `@bot_username ...` → expected: only that bot replies\n3. Verify that user `6053576134` can run commands successfully after restart.\n4. Build a mapping table for all 34 agents:\n   - agent ID\n   - Telegram bot username\n   - display name\n   - avatar/icon status\n5. Decide policy for public speaking:\n   - default only `@master_orchestrator_bot` handles broad requests, and specialists reply only when explicitly mentioned, or\n   - any mentioned specialist may reply directly while `master-orchestrator` still coordinates multi-agent work.\n6. If desired, extend config per Telegram account once usernames/account IDs are known.\n7. Rotate any exposed Telegram bot token in BotFather and update `/root/.openclaw/openclaw.json`.\n\n## Critical Context\n- Duplicate token check result:\n  - `/root/.openclaw/openclaw.json`\n  - 35 token fields found\n  - duplicates:\n    - `$.channels.telegram.accounts.senior-architect_bot.botToken`\n    - `$.channels.telegram.accounts.senior-backend_bot.botToken`\n    - `$.channels.telegram.accounts.stitch-loop_bot.botToken`\n    - `$.channels.telegram.accounts.typescript-reviewer_bot.botToken`\n- Relevant installed OpenClaw source references:\n  - `/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/bot-ClNJQIfx.js`\n    - contains:\n      - `if (policyAccess.reason === \"group-chat-not-allowed\") return await sendAuthMessage(\"This group is not allowed.\");`\n      - `return await sendAuthMessage(\"You are not authorized to use this command.\");`\n      - auth/mention logic around `hasBotMention`, `resolveCommandAuthorizedFromAuthorizers`, `registerTelegramNativeCommands`\n  - `/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/channel-94kVnXDM.js`\n    - confirms Telegram group config resolution from:\n      - `cfg.channels?.telegram?.accounts?.[accountId]?.groups`\n      - or `cfg.channels?.telegram?.groups`\n  - `/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/access-B1I79MZ7.js`\n  - `/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/commands-models-70xwb3QF.js`\n- Current config now targets:\n  ```json\n  \"channels\": {\n    \"telegram\": {\n      \"groupPolicy\": \"allowlist\",\n      \"allowFrom\": [\"6053576134\"],\n      \"groups\": {\n        \"-5212380728\": {\n          \"enabled\": true,\n          \"requireMention\": true\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n  ```\n- Previous old group discovered from runtime log and then later removed:\n  - group ID: `-1003833817951`\n  - title: `Maiychrus Company .Ltd`\n- Current active group requested by user:\n  - `-5212380728`\n- User ID explicitly allowlisted:\n  - `6053576134`\n- Gateway/runtime status earlier showed:\n  - config path in use: `~/.openclaw/openclaw.json`\n  - logs: `/tmp/openclaw/openclaw-2026-04-11.log`\n- Exact user-facing errors encountered:\n  - `\"This group is not allowed.\"`\n  - `\"You are not authorized to use this command.\"`\n- There was a system instruction later in the conversation to read `HEARTBEAT.md`; assistant responded `HEARTBEAT_OK`. No additional workspace action was taken from that.\n- Architecture guidance already given to user:\n  - do not let 34 bots freely auto-chat in one group\n  - preferred model is orchestrated coordination by `master-orchestrator`\n  - if user wants true visual bot identity per reply, each agent must be a separate Telegram bot account with its own username/avatar.\n\n---\n\n**Turn Context (split turn):**\n\n## Original Request\n[User asked to configure OpenClaw agents so the default thinking mode is `medium`, while key/core agents use `high`.]\n\n## Early Progress\n- [Assistant inspected `/root/.openclaw/openclaw.json` to check current agent config.]\n- [Found `agents.defaults` contains `model`, `skills`, `workspace`, `models`, `subagents`, but no `thinking` field set.]\n- [Checked sample agents in `agents.list`; their `thinking` values were also `None`/unset.]\n- [Assistant then started verifying whether `thinking` is a supported config field in OpenClaw schema/docs for both `agents.defaults` and per-agent overrides.]\n\n## Context for Suffix\n- [Current config state: default model is `ahvholding/AHV-Holding-TroLy` with fallback `ahvholding/AHV-Holding-DEV`; no `thinking` configured anywhere yet.]\n- [Recent work in suffix begins with a grep/search through OpenClaw installed files to confirm support for the `thinking` property.]\n- [Goal remains: update config so all agents inherit `medium`, and selected important agents are explicitly set to `high`.]\n\n<read-files>\n/root/.openclaw/openclaw.json\n/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/skills/master-orchestrator/SKILL.md\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/access-B1I79MZ7.js\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/bot-ClNJQIfx.js\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/channel-94kVnXDM.js\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/channel-policy-CrbswhIK.js\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/group-access-hrkZp9Cg.js\n</read-files>",
